---
alwaysApply: true
---

Use the C/C++ code style defined in the .editorconfig file as the baseline, and treat the rules in this file as extensions and amendments.

General
-------
- Use spaces only, never tabs.
- Indent with 4 spaces.
- Treat tab width as 4 only when reading existing code.
- Preserve semantics; change formatting only unless explicitly asked otherwise.

Indentation
-----------
- Do not indent braces relative to the owning statement.
- For multiline expressions, indent relative to the innermost open parenthesis.
- Indent wrapped content inside parentheses normally.
- Do not preserve irregular original indentation inside parentheses; normalize it.
- Indent namespace contents.
- Do not indent access specifiers inside classes.
- Keep preprocessor directives at column 0.
- Do not preserve irregular comment indentation; normalize it.
- Indent case labels inside switch blocks.
- Indent statements under case labels.
- If a case contains an explicit block, do not add extra indentation beyond the block itself.
- Indent lambda braces normally when the lambda is used as a parameter.
- goto labels should be one indent level left of normal statements in the same block.

Brace Placement
---------------
- Preserve local/project style for brace placement of namespace, type, function, block, and lambda opening braces if existing style is clear.
- Do not force scope braces onto isolated lines beyond normal formatting.
- Empty class/struct bodies must not use `{}` on one line.
- Empty function bodies must not use `{}` on one line.
- Keep `else` on the same line as the preceding `}`.
- Keep `catch` on the same line as the preceding `}`.
- Keep `while` in `do { ... } while (...)` on the same line as the preceding `}`.

Spacing
-------
- No space before function call/declaration `(`.
- No spaces inside function parameter parentheses.
- Empty parameter list must be `()`, not `( )`.
- One space after control-flow keywords: `if (` `for (` `while (` `switch (` `catch (`.
- No spaces inside control-flow parentheses.
- No space between lambda capture `[]` and lambda parameter `(`.
- No spaces inside cast parentheses.
- No extra space after cast close parenthesis.
- No spaces inside ordinary expression parentheses.
- One space before block-opening `{`.
- Empty braces use `{}`, not `{ }` when single-token form is allowed.
- No space before initializer-list `{` in `Type{...}`.
- Use spaces inside initializer-list braces: `{ 1, 2 }`.
- Preserve readable/aligned spacing inside initializer lists if already present.
- No space before `[`.
- No spaces inside `[]`.
- Empty brackets must be `[]`, not `[ ]`.
- Keep adjacent bracket groups together: `matrix[i][j]`, not `matrix[i] [j]`.
- No spaces inside lambda capture brackets.
- Empty lambda capture must be `[]`, not `[ ]`.
- No space before comma.
- One space after comma.
- No spaces around `.` and `->`.
- One space before inheritance colon.
- One space before constructor initializer colon.
- No space before semicolon.
- One space after semicolon when followed by another token, e.g. in `for`.
- No spaces around unary operators.
- One space around binary operators.
- One space around assignment operators.
- Pointer/reference alignment is left: `int* ptr`, `const Foo& ref`.
- One space around ternary `?` and `:`.

One-line Blocks
---------------
- Preserve reasonable one-line blocks when appropriate, e.g. `if (!ok) { return; }`.
- Expand to multiline when readability clearly benefits.

Includes
--------
- Missing includes are suggestions, not hard errors.
- Removing unused includes is allowed but should be done carefully.
- Include optimization is a suggestion, not mandatory.
- Do not auto-sort includes unless explicitly requested.
- Unsorted includes are acceptable unless project style says otherwise.
- Include sorting, if done, is case-insensitive.
- Prefer quoted/local include grouping consistent with project style.
- Use forward slashes in include paths.
- Do not invent a custom include policy if the project already has one.

Function Parameter Layout
-------------------------
- These rules apply to function declarations and definitions.

1. No parameters:
    - Keep `()` on the same line.
    - Example:
        `void foo();`

2. Exactly one parameter:
    - Compare the visual length of the parameter against the function name only.
    - Do not include return type or calling convention in the comparison.
    - If the parameter is shorter than the function name:
        - keep it inline: `foo(int value);`
    - If the parameter is longer than the function name:
        - break after `(`
        - put the parameter on the next line
        - put `)` or `);` on its own next line

3. Two or more parameters:
    - If the parameter list wraps, put one parameter per line.
    - Put the closing `)` or `);` on its own line after the last parameter.

4. Wrapped parameter list closing rule:
    - If parameters span multiple lines, closing `)` must be on its own line.
    - If the declaration ends with `;`, use `);` on its own line.
    - If it is a definition, place `)` on its own line before the function body, unless the local brace style clearly requires otherwise.

Examples
--------
- Good:
    VKAPI_ATTR VkResult VKAPI_CALL IMPL_vkAcquireNextImage2KHR(
        VkDevice device,
        const VkAcquireNextImageInfoKHR* acquire_info,
        uint32_t* image_index
    );

- Good:
    void process(int value);

- Good:
    VKAPI_ATTR VkResult VKAPI_CALL IMPL_vkSetPrivateDataEXT(
        const VkDevicePrivateDataCreateInfoEXT* private_data_create_info
    );

- Good:
    void foo();

Naming
------
Macros
- Always use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.
- Use only uppercase letters, digits, and underscores.
- Separate words with underscores.
- Avoid generic/conflicting names such as:
    - MIN
    - MAX
    - ERROR
    - SUCCESS
    - CHECK
    - VERSION
    - NONE
    - STATUS
- Prefer project/module/subsystem prefixes for non-local macros.
- Good:
    - NVK_MAX_IMAGE_COUNT
    - IMPL_VK_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_NS
    - DRIVER_LOG_ERROR

Types
- Use PascalCase for C++ class names, struct names, enum type names, and other user-defined types.
- Type names should be nouns or noun phrases.
- Type names should describe what the object is, not what it does.
- Good:
    - ImageCache
    - DeviceMemoryInfo
    - PresentQueueState

C++ Functions
- Use camelCase.
- Prefer verb-noun phrasing for action functions.
- Names must be descriptive enough to understand intent without reading implementation.
- Avoid vague names such as:
    - doStuff
    - handle
    - process
    - run
- Good:
    - getName
    - sendEmail
    - calculateTotal
    - updatePresentState
    - createSwapchainImage

C++ Boolean Functions
- Use boolean-style prefixes:
    - is
    - has
    - should
    - can
    - needs
- Good:
    - isValid
    - hasPermission
    - shouldRetry
    - canPresentNow
    - needsRebuild

C++ Variables
- Use camelCase for:
    - local variables
    - parameters
    - member variables
    - other non-type object names
- Use descriptive names.
- Boolean variables should read naturally as true/false state.
- Avoid overly short names except obvious short-lived loop indices.
- Good:
    - imageIndex
    - acquireInfo
    - totalSize
    - isEnabled
    - hasPendingWork

Pure C Functions
- Use snake_case.
- Prefer verb-noun phrasing.
- Names must be descriptive.
- Good:
    - get_name
    - send_email
    - calculate_total
    - update_present_state

Pure C Boolean Functions
- Use prefixes:
    - is_
    - has_
    - should_
    - can_
    - needs_
- Good:
    - is_valid
    - has_permission
    - should_retry

Pure C Variables
- Use snake_case for:
    - local variables
    - parameters
    - struct fields in pure C
    - static file-scope variables in pure C
- Use descriptive names.
- Boolean variables should read naturally as true/false state.
- Good:
    - image_index
    - acquire_info
    - total_size
    - is_enabled
    - has_pending_work

Language-Based Naming Selection
-------------------------------
- Macros in both C and C++: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- C++ classes/structs/types: PascalCase
- C++ functions: camelCase
- C++ variables: camelCase
- Pure C functions: snake_case
- Pure C variables: snake_case

Operational Priority
--------------------
When generating or rewriting code, prioritize in this order:
1. Preserve semantics
2. Match existing local/project style where rules explicitly say to preserve local style
3. Apply hard spacing/indentation rules
4. Apply function parameter layout rules
5. Apply naming rules
6. Avoid unnecessary rewrites outside the requested scope